# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: puppeteer-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] The term **asynchronous** refers to two or more objects or events that do not exist or happen at the same time, that is, they are **not** synchronous.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] When multiple related things happen without any being dependent on the completion of previous happenings, they are asynchronous.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] In computing, the word "asynchronous" is used in two major contexts, as explained below.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] Asynchronous communication is a method of exchanging messages in which the sending, receiving, and processing of each message is not dependent on the sending, receipt, or processing of other messages.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] In asynchronous communication, each party receives and processes messages when convenient or possible to do so, rather than doing so immediately upon receipt.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] Additionally, messages may be sent without waiting for acknowledgement, with the understanding that if a problem occurs, the recipient will request corrections or otherwise handle the situation.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] Email is a type of asynchronous human communication.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] The recipient reads the email and responds to it (or not) at their convenience, not necessarily right away.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] All parties can continue to send and receive messages at any time.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] Emails don't have to be scheduled in a particular sequence.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] In asynchronous software, making a request, such as to a server, does not block other processes while waiting for the response.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] The software can continue performing other tasks.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] For example, in promise-based APIs, `Promise` objects are created for long operations.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] After the operation is complete, the promise is handled.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] With promises, the software doesn't have to wait for the operation to finish.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] Asynchronous software design expands upon the concept by building code that allows a program to ask that a task be performed alongside the original task (or tasks), without stopping to wait for the task to complete.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] When the secondary task is completed, the original task is notified using an agreed-upon mechanism so that it knows the work is done, and that the result, if any, is available.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] There are a number of programming techniques for implementing asynchronous software.
[src:puppeteer-automation/asynchronous] See the article Asynchronous JavaScript for an introduction to them.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] A **headless browser** is a web browser without a graphical user interface.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but they are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] They are particularly useful for testing web pages as they are able to render and understand HTML the same way a browser would, including styling elements such as page layout, color, font selection and execution of JavaScript and Ajax which are usually not available when using other testing methods.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Since version 59 of Google Chrome and version 56 of Firefox, there is native support for remote control of the browser.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] This made earlier efforts obsolete, notably PhantomJS.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Headless browsers are also useful for web scraping.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Google stated in 2009 that using a headless browser could help their search engine index content from websites that use Ajax.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] However, a study of browser traffic in 2018 found no preference by malicious actors for headless browsers.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] There is no indication that headless browsers are used more frequently than non-headless browsers for malicious purposes, like DDoS attacks, SQL injections or cross-site scripting attacks.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] As several major browsers natively support headless mode through APIs, some software exists to perform browser automation through a unified interface.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Some test automation software and frameworks include headless browsers as part of their testing apparati.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Another approach is to use software that provides browser APIs.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] For example, Deno provides browser APIs as part of its design.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] For Node.js, jsdom is the most complete provider.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] While most are able to support common browser features (HTML parsing, cookies, XHR, some JavaScript, etc.), they do not render the DOM and have limited support for DOM events.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] They usually perform faster than full browsers, but are unable to correctly interpret many popular websites.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] Another is HtmlUnit, a headless browser written in Java.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] HtmlUnit uses the Rhino engine to provide JavaScript and Ajax support as well as partial rendering capability.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] These are various software that provide headless browser APIs.
[src:puppeteer-automation/headless-browser] An earlier effort (2008) was envjs from John Resig, which was a simulated browser environment written in JavaScript for the Rhino engine.
[src:puppeteer-automation/pptr-dev] Modern package managers (including npm (see the RFC), pnpm, Yarn, Bun, and Deno) block dependency install scripts by default.
[src:puppeteer-automation/pptr-dev] If the install script is blocked, Puppeteer will not download the browser during installation, leading to runtime errors.
[src:puppeteer-automation/pptr-dev] Alternatively, you can configure your package manager to allow the install script to run (for example, with npm, by adding `"puppeteer"` to `"allowScripts"` in your `package.json`).
[src:puppeteer-automation/pptr-dev] Install `chrome-devtools-mcp`, a Puppeteer-based MCP server for browser automation and debugging.
[src:puppeteer-automation/pptr-dev] Puppeteer also supports the experimental WebMCP API.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Scraping a web page involves fetching it and then extracting data from it.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Fetching is the downloading of a page (which a browser does when a user views a page).
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Therefore, web crawling is a main component of web scraping, to fetch pages for later processing.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Having fetched, extraction can take place.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The content of a page may be parsed, searched and reformatted, and its data copied into a spreadsheet or loaded into a database.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Web scrapers typically take something out of a page, to make use of it for another purpose somewhere else.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] An example would be finding and copying names and telephone numbers, companies and their URLs, or e-mail addresses to a list (contact scraping).
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Another example is collecting competitors product prices for marketing purposes, which can involve gathering large-scale pricing datasets from e-commerce websites and analysing them using data science techniques such as trend analysis, predictive modelling, and competitive benchmarking.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Web pages are built using text-based markup languages (HTML and XHTML), and frequently contain a wealth of data in text form.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] However, most web pages are designed for human end-users and not for ease of automated use.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] As a result, specialized tools and software have been developed to facilitate the scraping of web pages.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Web scraping applications include market research, price comparison, content monitoring and artificial intelligence.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Businesses rely on web scraping services to efficiently gather and utilize this data.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Newer forms of web scraping involve monitoring data feeds from web servers.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] For example, JSON is commonly used as a transport mechanism between the client and the web server.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] There are methods that some websites use to prevent web scraping, such as detecting and disallowing bots from crawling (viewing) their pages.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In response, web scraping systems use techniques involving DOM parsing, computer vision and natural language processing to simulate human-like browsing to enable gathering web page content for offline parsing.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] After the birth of the World Wide Web in 1989, the first web robot, World Wide Web Wanderer, was created in June 1993, which was intended only to measure the size of the web.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In December 1993, the first crawler-based web search engine, JumpStation, was launched.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] As there were fewer websites available on the web, search engines at that time used to rely on human administrators to collect and format links.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In comparison, Jump Station was the first WWW search engine to rely on a web robot.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In 2000, the first Web API and API crawler were created.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In 2000, Salesforce and eBay launched their own API, with which programmers could access and download some of the data available to the public.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Since then, many websites offer web APIs for people to access their public database.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Data extraction techniques range from manual collection to sophisticated automated systems.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Advanced methods analyze the underlying structure of web pages to transform unstructured content into a machine-readable format.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] These techniques utilize text processing or artificial intelligence, aligning with the technical goals of the Semantic Web.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The simplest form of web scraping is manual copying and pasting of data from a web page into a text file or spreadsheet.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] This approach requires no technical tools and can be used when automated scraping is blocked by website restrictions or when human judgment is necessary to interpret complex content.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] However, manual scraping is highly inefficient for large datasets, as it is time-consuming, prone to human error, and mentally exhausting.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] For this reason, it is generally considered impractical compared to automated methods, except in cases where automation is not feasible.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] A simple approach to extract information from web pages is to use the UNIX grep command or regular expression-matching facilities of programming languages (for instance Perl or Python), in order to find text matching a specified pattern.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Static and dynamic web pages can be retrieved by posting HTTP requests to the remote web server using socket programming.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Many websites have large collections of pages generated dynamically from an underlying structured source, like a database.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Data of the same category are typically encoded into similar pages by a common script or template.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In data mining, a program that detects such templates in a particular information source, extracts its content, and translates it into a relational form, is called a wrapper.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Wrapper generation algorithms assume that input pages of a wrapper induction system conform to a common template and that they can be easily identified in terms of a URL common scheme.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Moreover, some semi-structured data query languages, such as XQuery and the HTQL, can be used to parse HTML pages and to retrieve and transform page content.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] By using a program such as Selenium or Playwright, developers can control a web browser such as Chrome or Firefox to load, navigate, and retrieve data from websites.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] This method can be especially useful for scraping data from dynamic sites since a web browser will fully load each page.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Once an entire page is loaded, developers can access and parse the DOM using an expression language such as XPath.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] There are several companies that have developed vertical specific harvesting platforms.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] These platforms create and monitor a multitude of "bots" for specific verticals with no "man in the loop" (no direct human involvement), and no work related to a specific target site.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The preparation involves establishing the knowledge base for the entire vertical and then the platform creates the bots automatically.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The platform's robustness is measured by the quality of the information it retrieves (usually number of fields) and its scalability (how quick it can scale up to hundreds or thousands of sites).
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] This scalability is mostly used to target the Long Tail of sites that common aggregators find complicated or too labor-intensive to harvest content from.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The pages being scraped may embrace metadata or semantic markups and annotations, which can be used to locate specific data snippets.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] If the annotations are embedded in the pages, as Microformat does, this technique can be viewed as a special case of DOM parsing.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In another case, the annotations, organized into a semantic layer, are stored and managed separately from the web pages, so the scrapers can retrieve data schema and instructions from this layer before scraping the pages.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] There are efforts using machine learning and computer vision that attempt to identify and extract information from web pages by interpreting pages visually as a human being might.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The legality of web scraping varies across the world.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In general, web scraping may be against the terms of service of some websites, but the enforceability of these terms is unclear.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In the United States, website owners can use three major legal claims to prevent undesired web scraping: (1) copyright infringement (compilation), (2) violation of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act ("CFAA"), and (3) trespass to chattel.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] However, the effectiveness of these claims relies upon meeting various criteria, and the case law is still evolving.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] For example, with regard to copyright, while outright duplication of original expression will in many cases be illegal, in the United States the courts ruled in *Feist Publications v.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Rural Telephone Service* that duplication of facts is allowable.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] U.S. courts have acknowledged that users of "scrapers" or "robots" may be held liable for committing trespass to chattels, which involves a computer system itself being considered personal property upon which the user of a scraper is trespassing.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Bidder's Edge*, resulted in an injunction ordering Bidder's Edge to stop accessing, collecting, and indexing auctions from the eBay web site.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] This case involved automatic placing of bids, known as auction sniping.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Not all cases of web spidering brought before the courts have been considered trespass to chattels.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] One of the first major tests of screen scraping involved American Airlines (AA), and a firm called FareChase.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] AA successfully obtained an injunction from a Texas trial court, stopping FareChase from selling software that enables users to compare online fares if the software also searches AA's website.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The airline argued that FareChase's websearch software trespassed on AA's servers when it collected the publicly available data.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] FareChase filed an appeal in March 2003.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] By June, FareChase and AA agreed to settle and the appeal was dropped.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines has also challenged screen-scraping practices, and has involved both FareChase and another firm, Outtask, in a legal claim.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Southwest Airlines charged that the screen-scraping is Illegal since it is an example of "Computer Fraud and Abuse" and has led to "Damage and Loss" and "Unauthorized Access" of Southwest's site.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] It also constitutes "Interference with Business Relations", "Trespass", and "Harmful Access by Computer".
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] They also claimed that screen-scraping constitutes what is legally known as "Misappropriation and Unjust Enrichment", as well as being a breach of the web site's user agreement.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Outtask denied all these claims, claiming that the prevailing law, in this case, should be US Copyright law and that under copyright, the pieces of information being scraped would not be subject to copyright protection.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Although the cases were never resolved in the Supreme Court of the United States, FareChase was eventually shuttered by parent company Yahoo!, and Outtask was purchased by travel expense company Concur.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In 2012, a startup called 3Taps scraped classified housing ads from Craigslist.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Craigslist sent 3Taps a cease-and-desist letter and blocked their IP addresses and later sued, in *Craigslist v.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The court held that the cease-and-desist letter and IP blocking was sufficient for Craigslist to properly claim that 3Taps had violated the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA).
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Although these are early scraping decisions, and the theories of liability are not uniform, it is difficult to ignore a pattern emerging that the courts are prepared to protect proprietary content on commercial sites from uses which are undesirable to the owners of such sites.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] While the law in this area becomes more settled, entities contemplating using scraping programs to access a public web site should also consider whether such action is authorized by reviewing the terms of use and other terms or notices posted on or made available through the site.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Eventbrite Inc.* (2010), the United States district court for the eastern district of Virginia, ruled that the terms of use should be brought to the users' attention in order for a browsewrap contract or license to be enforceable.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In a 2014 case, filed in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania, e-commerce site QVC objected to the Pinterest-like shopping aggregator Resultly's 'scraping of QVC's site for real-time pricing data.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] QVC alleges that Resultly "excessively crawled" QVC's retail site (allegedly sending 200-300 search requests to QVC's website per minute, sometimes to up to 36,000 requests per minute) which caused QVC's site to crash for two days, resulting in lost sales for QVC.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] QVC's complaint alleges that the defendant disguised its web crawler to mask its source IP address and thus prevented QVC from quickly repairing the problem.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] This is a particularly interesting scraping case because QVC is seeking damages for the unavailability of their website, which QVC claims was caused by Resultly.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In the plaintiff's web site during the period of this trial, the terms of use link are displayed among all the links of the site, at the bottom of the page as most sites on the internet.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] This ruling contradicts the Irish ruling described below.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The court also rejected the plaintiff's argument that the browse-wrap restrictions were enforceable in view of Virginia's adoption of the Uniform Computer Information Transactions Act (UCITA)—a uniform law that many believed was in favor on common browse-wrap contracting practices.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Power Ventures, Inc.*, a district court ruled in 2012 that Power Ventures could not scrape Facebook pages on behalf of a Facebook user.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The case is on appeal, and the Electronic Frontier Foundation filed a brief in 2015 asking that it be overturned.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Holdings, Inc.*, a court in the US held Meltwater liable for scraping and republishing news information from the Associated Press, but a court in the United Kingdom held in favor of Meltwater.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The Ninth Circuit ruled in 2019 that web scraping did not violate the CFAA in *hiQ Labs v.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The case was appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which returned the case to the Ninth Circuit to reconsider the case in light of the 2021 Supreme Court decision in *Van Buren v.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] United States* which narrowed the applicability of the CFAA.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] On this review, the Ninth Circuit upheld their prior decision.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Internet Archive collects and distributes a significant number of publicly available web pages without being considered to be in violation of copyright laws.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In February 2006, the Danish Maritime and Commercial Court (Copenhagen) ruled that systematic crawling, indexing, and deep linking by portal site ofir.dk of real estate site Home.dk does not conflict with Danish law or the database directive of the European Union.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Ethical data scraping supports offmarket sourcing in business but must comply with GDPR to avoid privacy violations in automated data collection.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In a February 2010 case complicated by matters of jurisdiction, Ireland's High Court delivered a verdict that illustrates the inchoate state of developing case law.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In the case of *Ryanair Ltd v Billigfluege.de GmbH*, Ireland's High Court ruled Ryanair's "click-wrap" agreement to be legally binding.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The decision is under appeal in Ireland's Supreme Court.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] On April 30, 2020, the French Data Protection Authority (CNIL) released new guidelines on web scraping.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The CNIL guidelines made it clear that publicly available data is still personal data and cannot be repurposed without the knowledge of the person to whom that data belongs.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] In Australia, the Spam Act 2003 outlaws some forms of web harvesting, although this only applies to email addresses.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] Besides a few cases dealing with IPR infringement, Indian courts have not expressly ruled on the legality of web scraping.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] However, since all common forms of electronic contracts are enforceable in India, violating the terms of use prohibiting data scraping will be a violation of the contract law.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] It will also violate the Information Technology Act, 2000, which penalizes unauthorized access to a computer resource or extracting data from a computer resource.
[src:puppeteer-automation/web-scraping] The administrator of a website can use various measures to stop or slow a bot.
